<text>Molecular Crystals and Crystal Melting
p. 5 of 8

Molecular crystals are formed by one or more kind of molecule of covalently bonded atoms held together in regular patterns.  But the force of  attractions (van der Waals), represented here by dotted lines between molecules, when you click the &quot;Show VDW interactions&quot;,  are the same for atoms and molecules alike.  As you have seen, these forces have an effect only if the atoms or molecules are close enough. They keep the atoms or molecules fixed in their positions and prevent them from moving away from their neighbors. 

It takes energy to overcome the strength of the forces, and when enough energy is added, a phase change occurs. 

 
 * 

The above model shows a crystal formed by the molecule A3B8 at 100 K. The green particles represent A and the white ones represent B.
1. Run the model, and then raise the temperature, one tick (marker) at a time.
2. Take a snapshot when you see &quot;melting&quot; and then continue to run the model until you achieve complete melting.  Take another snapshot.    

 At what temperature does it appear to melt?  What is the first sign of melting?

 

 After the molecular crystal is molten, try lowering the temperature to see if you can get it recrystallized. Did you succeed? Take a   of your best effort. Compare this with the easy recrystallization of a non-molecular crystal formed by a simple material. 

What is your theory of why it is hard to recrystallize a molecular crystal that has been melted?

 

  
*K=Kelvin, a temperature scale with an absolute zero.

   

